UNDIAGNOSED SKIN DISEASE - BRAZIL (PERNAMBUCO) REQUEST FOR INFORMATION
**********************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Fri 26 Nov 2021
Source: Catholic Transcript [edited]
https://www.catholictranscript.org/outbreaks-of-skin-diseases-reach-new-municipalities/


The mysterious outbreak of the new skin disease in Pernambuco [previously reported in ProMED-PORT. - Mod.SH] has affected more and more people. This Thursday [25 Nov 2021], 5 other cities in the state (Cabo de Santo Agostinho, Igaraso [Igarassu], Ipojuca, Itabisuma [Itapissuma], and Nazari da Mata) have reported cases of residents with symptoms such as itching and skin lesions. In total, 11 municipalities are affected by the disease, representing about 300 cases, according to city councils. In Recife, the first cases were recorded in early October [2021].

Symptoms include itching, bump-shaped lesions, and redness. The cause of the disease is not yet known, but investigations have been carried out by the city council and the health department of Pernambuco to find out the cause of the outbreak.

After a technical note was sent last Friday [19 Nov 2021] to the health services that all cases of skin diseases with their own symptoms should be reported for disease action mapping, SES-PE [Secretaria de Saúde de Pernambuco - Pernambuco state public health department], with the support of city halls, has sought to find the cause of the outbreak.

According to the department, the investigation was carried out by the technical team of SES-PE itself, from the Central Laboratory of Pernambuco (Lacen-PE) and other specialists. So far, the cause of the disease is unknown, but hypotheses include scabies, viral infections (dengue, Zika virus, chikungunya), allergic reactions and even environmental imbalances.

Cases were investigated in clinical, epidemiological and laboratory investigations, as reported on [19 Nov 2021] by the executive secretary of health surveillance, Marcela Abath, in a meeting with the State Department of Health and the Agio Magalhaes Institute. At a press conference on Thursday [25 Nov 2021], health minister Andre Longo confirmed that biopsies had been carried out in order to find out the cause of the disease.

[byline: Yvonne Lipsey]

[A photo of the skin lesions is available at the source URL. - Mod.ML]

